  "why": "CAGFuzz enforces semantic consistency and naturalness via deep-feature similarity (VGG-19) and CycleGAN cycle-consistency losses, and it filters/generated mutants using a cosine-similarity threshold (e.g., >0.9). However, the paper computes similarity between the current parent and each new mutant (i.e., successive mutation steps) and places promising mutants back into the processing pool for further mutation. The design therefore constrains realism/semantics only relative to the immediate previous input rather than always relative to the original seed, which allows cumulative drift across multiple iterations. Thus the approach enforces plausibility only between successive mutation steps (Medium).",
  "evidence": "Page 5, Section 3.1 (Overview): \"Then, we calculate the cosine similarity (see Section 3.3.3) between the deep features of the original and the adversarial examples. If the cosine similarity between the two deep features is more than 0.9, we assume that the adversarial example is consistent with the original example in deep features and can be saved.\"; Page 5, Algorithm 1 (main loop): \"data = AEG(parent); Fp; Fd = FeatureExtraction(parent; data); Similarity = CosineSimilarity(Fp; Fd);\" (shows similarity is computed against the selected parent, i.e., successive mutant); Page 6-7, Section 3.2.2 (Training Adversarial Example Generator): \"we add constraints to the perturbations, and control the degree of mutations through the cycle consistency loss... the perturbations added to the original example are invisible.\"; Page 8, Section 3.3.3 (Cosine Similarity Computation): \"Cosine similarity is used to measure the difference between the adversarial example and the original example... To control the size and improve the mutation quality of adversarial examples, we select the top-k adversarial examples whose cosine similarity is sorted descendingly as eligible examples to continue the follow-up steps.\""
